paragraphs.text:
%md
# Apache Zeppelin Tutorial 1
Apache Zeppelin is a multi-purpose notebook which supports 20+ language backends. It is designed for:

* Data Ingestion
* Data Discovery
* Data Analytics
* Data Visualization & Collaboration

For [more details](http://zeppelin.apache.org/docs/0.8.1/index.html)

In this tutorial, we will cover:
1. Get Started with Local Files
2. Basic Display System
3. Dynamic Form

msg.data:
Apache Zeppelin Tutorial 1

Apache Zeppelin is a multi-purpose notebook which supports 20+ language backends. It is designed for:

  • Data Ingestion
  • Data Discovery
  • Data Analytics
  • Data Visualization & Collaboration

For more details

In this tutorial, we will cover:
1. Get Started with Local Files
2. Basic Display System
3. Dynamic Form

paragraphs.text: %md ## 1. Get Started with Local Files Current main backend processing engine of Zeppelin is [Apache Spark](https://spark.apache.org/). If you're new to this system, you might want to start by getting an idea of [how it processes data](https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/quick-start.html) to get the most out of Zeppelin. ### Data Transformation In this tutorial, we will use sample data [bank.zip](http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/00222/bank.zip) (then, extract it). More details about the [dataset](https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/bank+marketing). First, we transform `csv` format into `RDD` objects. For [more details](https://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/rdd-programming-guide.html).

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Data Retrieval
Use SQL to query the age information and Zeppelin will help you display the data distribution:

msg.data:
Data Retrieval

Use SQL to query the age information and Zeppelin will help you display the data distribution:

paragraphs.text:
%sql
select age, count(1) from bank where age < 30 group by age order by age

## 2. Basic Display System 
In Apache Zeppelin, You can display text, html, mathematical expressions, table, and network.

msg.data:
2. Basic Display System

In Apache Zeppelin, You can display text, html, mathematical expressions, table, and network.

paragraphs.title: Text
paragraphs.text:
%spark
print("%text Interactive browser-based notebooks enable data engineers, data analysts and data scientists to be more productive by developing, organizing, executing, and `sh` interactive browser-based notebooks enable data engineers, data analysts and data scientists to be more productive by developing, organizing, executing, and sharing data code and visualizing results without referring to the command line or needing the cluster details. Notebooks allow these users not only allow to execute but to interactively work with long workflows. There are a number of notebooks available with Spark. iPython remains a mature choice and great example of a data science notebook. Apache Zeppelin is a new and upcoming web-based notebook which brings data exploration, visualization, sharing, and collaboration features to Spark. It support Python, but also a growing list of programming languages such as Scala, Hive, SparkSQL, shell, and markdown. ")

Notebooks allow these users not only allow to execute but to interactively work with long workflows. There are a number of notebooks available with Spark. iPython remains a mature choice and great example of a data science notebook. Apache Zeppelin is a new and upcoming web-based notebook which brings data exploration, visualization, sharing, and collaboration features to Spark. It support Python, but also a growing list of programming languages such as Scala, Hive, SparkSQL, shell, and markdown.

paragraphs.title: Mathematical Expressions
paragraphs.text:
%md

HTML display system automatically formats mathematical expression using [MathJax](https://www.mathjax.org/). You can use `\\( INLINE EXPRESSION \\)` and `$$ EXPRESSION $$` to format. For example,

When \\(a \\ne 0\\), there are two solutions to \\(ax^2 + bx + c = 0\\) and they are
$$x = {-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac} \over 2a}.$$

msg.data: name size %html sun 100 %html moon 10

Network

With the %network statement, Zeppelin treats your output as a graph. Your data must be described using the json format with the following params:

  • “nodes” (mandatory): list of nodes in the graph. Every node can have the following params:
    • “id” (mandatory): the id of the node (must be unique);
    • “label”: the main Label;
    • “labels”: the list of the labels;
    • “data”: the data attached to the node;
  • “edges”: list of the edges in the graph;
    • “id” (mandatory): the id of the edge (must be unique);
    • “source” (mandatory): the id of source node;
    • “target” (mandatory): the id of target node;
    • “label”: the main type of the edge;
    • “data”: the data attached to the edge;
  • “labels”: a map (K, V) where K is the node label and V is the color of the node;
  • “directed”: (true/false, default false) wich tells if is directed graph or not;
  • “types”: a distinct list of the edge types of the graph
